        <label>7</label>
        <p>The exceptions to this are studies of a predominantly demographic nature which, recognizing the significance of foetal mortality to rates of both reproductive mortality and fertility, have attempted to estimate long-term stillbirth trends in England and Wales over the last few centuries. See, in particular, <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="b61">Woods</xref>, &#x2018;Measurement of historical trends&#x2019;; <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="b63">Wrigley</xref>, <italic>Poverty, progress, and population</italic>, pp. 317&#x2013;50; <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="b48">Reid</xref>, &#x2018;Neonatal mortality&#x2019;; <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="b28">Hart</xref>, &#x2018;Beyond infant mortality&#x2019;; <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="b42">Mooney</xref>, &#x2018;Still-births&#x2019;.</p>
